{
  "doc_id": "21281",
  "text": "visible by interfacial interference fringes, in a glass monolith layer and glass/sapphire bilayer under load, for tests in surface loading with a hard sphere. The tensile stresses responsible for these fractures are 'flexural' in nature, [CITATION_1] and are much lower in magnitude than contact stresses but also much less concentrated. The radial cracks have initiated at the cementation surface beneath the contact and spread sideways and upward. Viewed from below, they are 'star-shaped' with multiple arms. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] They tend to close up during unloading, causing the interference fringe patterns to disappear and thus make detection difficult. The same cracks are even harder to detect in opaque or translucent ceramics until they break through to the top surface, or until delamination occurs at either the cementation or veneer/core interface. The stress state in the shells is a little more complex. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Fig. 4c and d shows radial cracks in resin-filled glass shell structures loaded with a hard and soft indenter, respectively. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] A hard contact initiates the same kind of radial cracks seen in Fig. 4a and b. A soft contact engulfs the top surface within a compression zone, suppressing radial cracking there and transferring tensile stresses to the margin [CITATION_8] -the result is the same kind of longitudinal fracture, at similar failure loads, but with the cracks propagating in an opposite direction. In all cases in Figs. 3 and 4 the fractures remain contained within the brittle outerlayer. Once radial cracks break through the shell thickness they progress slowly but inexorably with continued cycling around the side walls, under the influence of SCG. [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] The ensuing full fractures have all the essential characteristics of the clinical failures depicted in Fig. 1 . Even contacts that produce no evidence of surface damage in a single load cycle can lead to catastrophic crack growth over time. Severe overloads can lead to delamination or even penetration of the cracks into the dentine-like sublayer. [CITATION_11] ",
